    <main>
        <h1>If | Python</h1>
        <p>Introducing conditionals! Conditionals work so when an input returns true it'll execute code. Python is kinda different from other languagues. Python's syntax doesn't use {} or () instead we replace () by : and brackets by indents.</p>
        <div class="code">
            x = 1<br>
            if x == 1:<br>
                <indent/>print("Hello world!")
        </div>
        <p>This code will output Hello world becaus variable x's value is 1 and the if statement checks if the variable equals to 1. We'll leave you all the possible operators below this paragraph üòÅ.</p>
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>==</th>
                <th>!=</th>
                <th>></th>
                <th><</th>
                <th>in</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Equal</td>
                <td>Not equal</td>
                <td>Bigger than</td>
                <td>Smaller than</td>
                <td>Exists in array</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p>Sometimes we don't want to write a lot of ifs inside ifs so we use things like "or" and "and":</p>
        <div class="code">
            x = 3<br>
            if x == 1 or x == 3:<br>
                <indent/>print("Hello world")
        </div>
        <p>Outputs Hello world because x value must be either 1 or 3</p>
        <div class="code">
            age = 17<br>
            name = "xnotkingdev"<br>
            if age > 17 and name == "xnotkingdev":<br>
                <indent/>print("You're older than 18 and your name is xnotkingdev")
        </div>
        <p>Code above doesn't leave any output as the age is under 18.</p>
        <div class="next" onclick="location.href = '/python/ifelse'" style="background-color: wheat; padding: 10px; border-radius: 7px; width: 100%; text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">Next lesson</div>
    </main>
</Layout>
